05108nam a22009375i 9783110583441DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105834417 a10.1515/97831105834412doi  a(DE-B1597)490275  a(OCoLC)1046613869  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP211.5bE94 2018 7aLAN0110002bisacsh04a410  aGC 60872rvk0(DE-625)rvk/38512:1 aEvertz, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVisual Prosody :bThe Graphematic Foot in English and German /cMartin Evertz. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VIII, 239 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLinguistische Arbeiten ,x0344-6727 ;v57000tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Features, Letters and Graphemes -- t3. The Graphematic Syllable -- t4. The Graphematic Foot -- t5. Conclusion -- tBibliography -- tAppendix0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAccording to well-established views, language has several subsystems where each subsystem (e.g. syntax, morphology, phonology) operates on the basis of hierarchically organised units. When it comes to the graphematic structure of words, however, the received view appears to be that linear structure is all that matters. Contrary to this view, a sub-field of writing systems research emerges that can be called non-linear or supra-segmental graphematics. Drawing on parallels with supra-segmental phonology, supra-segmental graphematics claims the existence and relevance of cross-linguistically available building blocks, such as the syllable and the foot, in alphabetical writing systems, such as the writing systems of German and English. This book explores the graphematic hierarchy with a special focus on the unit foot. Structural, experimental and databased evidence is presented in favour of this approach. In addition, analyses within the optimality theory framework are offered. This work shows that the supra-segmental graphematic approaches are superior to linear ones with respect to explanatory strength and even preciseness of the description. It is thus interesting for academics concerned with writing systems and orthography teaching.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnglish languagexGraphemics. 0aGerman languagexGraphemics. 4aGraphematik. 4aHierarchische Struktur. 4aSilbe. 4aVersfuß. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Phonetics & Phonology.2bisacsh  aFoot.  aGraphematics.  aHierarchical Structure.  aSyllable.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2018 Part 1z978311076248808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z978311071955008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018 Englishz978311060407808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018z9783110603170oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831105811950 cprintz978311058108940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311058344140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110583441423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110583441/original  a978-3-11-060407-8  EBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-071955-0  DG Plus eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-076248-8  DG Plus DeG Package 2018 Part 1b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EB